		            		            		            					<!-- start content -->
					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><table border="1">
<tr>
<th>Graded Potentials</th>
<th>Action Potentials</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Amplitude varies the size of the initiating event.</td>
<td>All-or-none. Once the membrane is depolarized to threshold, amplitude is independent of the size of the initiating event.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Can be summed.</td>
<td>Cannot be summed.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Does not have a threshold.</td>
<td>Has a threshold (about 15 mV depolarized relative to the resting potential.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Does not have a refractory period.</td>
<td>Has a refractory period.</td>
<p><br />    
</p>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Is conducted decrimentally (amplitude decreases with distance).</td>
<td>Depolarization is amplified to a constant value at each point along the membrane.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Duration varies with inititiating condition.</td>
<td>Duration is constant under constant conditions.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Can be a depolariztion or a hyperpolarization.</td>
<td>Is only a depolariztion.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Initiated by environment (receptor), neurotransmitter (synapse), or spontaneously.</td>
<td>Initiated by a graded potential.</td>
</tr>



</table>

